    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n6845" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ὀπαῖος</span></b>  (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ὀπή</span>): <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">with an opening;</span> neut. pl. as
          subst., <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἀν᾽ ὀπαῖα</span> (v. l. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἀνοπαῖα</span>, q. v.), through the
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">loop-holes</span>, i. e. between the rafters under the
          eaves, <i><span class="en">Od. 1.320</span></i>†. These spaces were
          in later times closed, and termed specifically <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μετόπαι</span>. (See cut No. 83.)</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
